  "text": "## Health Check Endpoint Implementations Across Kubernetes, Grafana, and Prometheus\n\n### Kubernetes\n**Location**: `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz.go` and `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz/healthz.go`\n\nKubernetes implements a sophisticated health check system with three endpoints:\n- `/healthz` - Returns 200 when server is running (backwards compatibility)\n- `/livez` - Liveness probe indicating process is alive with configurable grace period\n- `/readyz` - Readiness probe indicating server has completed boot and can handle traffic\n\nThe implementation uses a `healthCheckRegistry` struct that manages health checkers for each endpoint. Key components:\n- `HealthChecker` interface with `Name()` and `Check(*http.Request) error` methods\n- `PingHealthz` - Always returns healthy\n- `LogHealthz` - Checks if logging subsystem is not blocked (must flush every 2 minutes)\n- `NewInformerSyncHealthz()` - Checks if all informer caches have synced\n- `NewShutdownHealthz()` - Fails when shutdown signal received\n- `AddHealthChecks()` - Adds checks to all three endpoints\n- `AddBootSequenceHealthChecks()` - Adds checks with grace period for livez\n- `AddReadyzChecks()` - Adds checks specific to readyz endpoint\n\nETCD storage health is verified via `EtcdHealthCheck()` function in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/etcd3/healthcheck.go` which decodes etcd's health status JSON.\n\nController-manager at `cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go` uses `NewMutableHealthzHandler` from the controller-manager library and adds per-controller health checkers through the `HealthCheckAdder` interface. Each controller registers a `NamedHealthChecker` that tracks the controller's operational status.\n\n### Grafana\n**Location**: `pkg/api/http_server.go` and `pkg/server/health.go`\n\nGrafana implements a simpler health check system:\n\n1. **Lightweight Endpoints**:\n   - `/healthz` - Returns 200 with \"Ok\" if web server is running (no checks)\n   - `/livez` - Always returns 200 (simple liveness indicator)\n   - `/readyz` - Returns 200 if `HealthNotifier.IsReady()` is true, else 503 Service Unavailable\n   - `/api/health` - Extended health endpoint that checks database connectivity\n\n2. **Health Tracking**:\n   - `HealthNotifier` struct uses `atomic.Bool` for thread-safe readiness state\n   - `SetReady()` and `SetNotReady()` methods allow operators to signal readiness\n   - `IsReady()` returns current ready state\n   - `LivezHandler()` always returns 200 OK\n   - `ReadyzHandler()` depends on HealthNotifier state\n\n3. **Database Checks**:\n   - `apiHealthHandler` at `/api/health` attempts database access and returns 503 if unavailable\n   - Returns version information unless anonymous mode hides version\n\n4. **Registration**:\n   - `RegisterHealthEndpoints()` registers `/livez` and `/readyz` on mux.Router\n   - `healthzHandler()` is middleware that intercepts `/healthz` requests\n   - `apiHealthHandler()` is middleware that intercepts `/api/health` requests\n\n### Prometheus\n**Location**: `web/web.go`\n\nPrometheus uses the simplest approach with startup-state-aware endpoints:\n\n1. **Endpoints**:\n   - `/-/healthy` - Liveness probe, always returns 200 with message \"{AppName} is Healthy.\"\n   - `/-/ready` - Readiness probe wrapped with `testReady()` middleware\n   - Both support GET and HEAD methods\n\n2. **Ready State Management**:\n   - `ReadyStatus` enum: `NotReady (0)`, `Ready (1)`, `Stopping (2)`\n   - Stored in atomic field `h.ready`\n   - `isReady()` method checks if status == Ready\n\n3. **Ready Wrapper**:\n   - `testReady(f http.HandlerFunc)` wraps handlers to enforce readiness\n   - Returns 200 OK with handler output if `Ready`\n   - Returns 503 Service Unavailable with \"Service Unavailable\" message if `NotReady` or `Stopping`\n   - Sets header `X-Prometheus-Stopping: true/false` to distinguish shutdown state\n\n4. **Usage**:\n   - Federation endpoint (`/federate`), consoles, and other sensitive operations use `readyf()` wrapper\n   - Metrics endpoint (`/metrics`) is always available regardless of ready state\n   - Version endpoint (`/version`) is always available\n\n### Key Differences\n\n1. **Complexity**: Kubernetes > Grafana > Prometheus\n2. **Dependency Checks**: \n   - Kubernetes: ETcd/storage, informer sync, logging, graceful shutdown\n   - Grafana: Database connectivity via `/api/health`\n   - Prometheus: Simple startup completion flag\n3. **Grace Periods**: Only Kubernetes implements configurable grace periods for liveness probes\n4. **Endpoint Naming**:\n   - Kubernetes: `/healthz`, `/livez`, `/readyz`\n   - Grafana: `/healthz`, `/api/health`, `/livez`, `/readyz`\n   - Prometheus: `/-/healthy`, `/-/ready`\n5. **Architecture**: Kubernetes uses pluggable checker interfaces, Grafana uses explicit handlers, Prometheus uses state-based wrappers"
}

